        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Tuesday was <a href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-11-01-2025-r2-9-christmas-for-orthodox-christians" target="_blank">Christmas for Orthodox Christians</a> around the world. Most Orthodox branches use the Julian calendar instead of the Gregorian one, which has a difference of 13 days between them. Some Orthodox Christians fast 40 days before, followed by a feast with 12 dishes representing Christ's apostles. Common foods include cabbage soup, baked apples, and Kutia, a honey and wheat dish. Many Serbians will burn an oak tree branch or even a tree on Christmas Eve. Ethiopians dress in white and stay up for all-night mass.</p>
